'''Lillie Glacier''' is a large , about 160 km (100 mi) long and 16 km (10 mi) wide, between  on the west and  and  on the east, flowing to  on the coast and forming the Lillie Glacier Tongue. The glacier tongue was discovered by the , 1910-13, and named for Dennis G. Lillie, biologist on the ''Terra Nova''. The name Lillie has since been extended to the entire glacier. The lower half of the glacier was plotted by  (Thala Dan), 1962, which explored the area and utilized air photos taken by  Operation Highjump, 1946-47. The whole feature was mapped by  from surveys and U.S. Navy air photos, 1960-62.